 Creating an automatically generated table of contents in LaTeX involves using the standard package `tableofcontents` and structuring your document with well-defined sections. Here's an example using the classical "article" document class. This example assumes you have nested sections (subsections) and a custom section title format.

1. First, ensure you include the `tableofcontents` package in the preamble of your LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tableofcontents} % For automatically generated table of contents
\usepackage{titlesec} % For customizing section titles

% Customize section titles using Titlesec package
\titleformat{\section}
  {\normalfont\fontsize{14}{15}\bfseries}{\thesection}{1em}{}
\titleformat{\subsection}
  {\normalfont\fontsize{12}{15}\bfseries}{\thesubscription}{0.5em}{}
```

2. Now, let's create some content with nested sections:

```latex
\section{Section One}
Content of Section One...

\subsection{Subsection 1.1}
More content about Subsection 1.1...

\subsection{Subsection 1.2}
More content about Subsection 1.2...

\section{Section Two}
Content of Section Two...

\subsection{Subsection 2.1}
More content about Subsection 2.1...

\subsection{Subsection 2.2}
More content about Subsection 2.2...
```

3. Compile your LaTeX document at least once to create the necessary index files for the table of contents. Then, generate the table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command in the document:

```latex
\tableofcontents % Place this command where you want the table of contents to appear, usually at the beginning of the document
```

4. Compile the document again to produce the PDF output with the automatically generated table of contents:

```bash
xelatex filename.tex % Or pdflatex, if you're not using XeLaTeX
```

The resulting PDF document will contain an up-to-date table of contents that reflects the structure and hierarchy of your sections and subsections. Remember that you only need to issue the table generation command (`\tableofcontents`) when you add, remove, or modify sections in your document; compiling the document again will update the table of contents accordingly.

