        for (long n : testCases) {
            System.out.printf("n = %d, isPowerOfThree = %b%n", n, isPowerOfThree(n));
        }
    }
}
```

This solution checks if `n` has an exact bit representation as a power of three by calculating its base-3 logarithm using `haveBitSetBit()`. If the result is an integer and satisfies the property that its binary representation has only set bits in groups of three (a power-of-two representation), then `n` is a power of three. Note that this solution assumes `n` is long integers, adjust the data type accordingly for larger or smaller integers.

Keep in mind that the `haveBitSetBit()` method is an optimization provided by some JVM implementations (like OpenJDK HotSpot) and may not be available in all JVMs or older versions. In such cases, you'll need to implement a custom logarithmic function or use recursive or looping solutions.

