 To create a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word, you can use the standard library files `ifstream` for reading input files, `string` for handling strings, and `vector` or `map` for storing and counting the occurrences. Here's an example using a `map` to store words as keys and their counts as values.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>

int main() {
    std::string filePath = "input.txt";
    std::string searchWord = "example"; // Set this to the word you want to search for
    std::ifstream file(filePath);
    std::map<std::string, int> wordCountMap;

    if (file.is_open()) {
        std::string line;
        int lineNumber = 1;

        while (getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos = line.find(searchWord); // Search for the word in the current line

            if (pos != std::string::npos) { // If the word is found
                ++wordCountMap[searchWord]; // Increment its count in the map
